{
  "id": "c-moma9llq-195259699140",
  "goal": "Implementation — turn the Laboratory MVP0 design into a working apparatus. Children decompose the build into commissionable units; each child becomes a brief + posted commission when ready to dispatch. First few items (framework verification, plugin reshape, schema/CLI) unblock everything else; engines and archive can parallelize once the skeleton lands.",
  "status": "concluded",
  "createdAt": "2026-05-01T02:18:06.110Z",
  "parentId": "c-mom18vmh-c1260c725e9f",
  "conclusion": "Laboratory apparatus implementation complete. All children concluded; first real-world trial (X016 phase 1, w-mondjwk9-5f18bff39e29) ran successfully end-to-end against vibers. The apparatus is live and producing reproducible trial data. Implementation summary: 5 phase orchestrators + 4 fixture/scenario engine pairs + 3 standard probes + archive engine + 4 CLI tools + per-trial framework-version pin via npx bootstrap + stable-pin enforcement at manifest load + 210 unit tests + codified pipeline smoke test + apparatus architecture doc + canonical spec at packages/laboratory/README.md. Two follow-up clicks open for grit surfaced during live runs: c-momm4abc (failed-trial orphan cleanup) and c-momm4i15 (daemon vs CLI Scriptorium drift). Next blocking work for X016 phase 2 (real implementer execution + orientation-tax measurement): add daemon lifecycle to lab.guild-setup — currently the test guild has no running spider crawl, so the rig template can post a commission but not drive it to completion.",
  "resolvedAt": "2026-05-01T20:40:16.532Z",
  "links": {
    "outbound": [],
    "inbound": []
  },
  "parent": {
    "id": "c-mom18vmh-c1260c725e9f",
    "goal": "Build the Laboratory apparatus — a general-purpose toolkit for running experiments on guild configurations. Audiences: nexus development (cost/quality tuning) and end users (evaluating their own prompts/plugins/configs). Architecture: experiment as first-class research unit; trial-runs as writ-shaped execution units; fixtures (setup/teardown with a dep DAG) decoupled from probes (data extraction); declarative scenarios + end-conditions; per-experiment analysis instruments. Lab runs in a 'real' guild that owns all experiment data; temp test-guilds are pure observation surfaces. Generalizes the P3 infrastructure spec (c-molveg89) into a reusable apparatus. Reuses the 'Laboratory' name (data-mirroring stub retired 2026-04-30 is internal-only).",
    "status": "live"
  },
  "children": {
    "summary": {
      "concluded": 16,
      "live": 4
    },
    "items": [
      {
        "id": "c-monewa82-702a5fbe7cd5",
        "goal": "lab.probe-trial-context: rigTemplate field captures null in practice. The probe reads spider.show(rigId) and tries to extract templateId/template from the rig doc with defensive fallbacks. Trial 1 captured rigTemplate=null even though the rig was instantiated from the registered laboratory.post-and-collect-default template. Need to investigate: does Spider's RigDoc actually carry the template id under some other field name? Or does it not store the source template at all post-spawn? If the latter, we may need to pull template name from a different source (e.g. the Spider's listTemplates() + matching by writ-type → mapping). Surfaced in X016 trial 1 (w-mondjwk9, archive lar-mondkc1h).",
        "status": "live"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-monew2rg-8653b2e5a6cc",
        "goal": "X016 phase 2 — full implementer execution + orientation-tax measurement. Add daemon lifecycle to lab.guild-setup so the test guild's Spider can drive the rig to completion. Likely shape: lab.guild-setup spawns a long-running 'nsg crawl-continual' (or 'nsg start') against the test guild after fixture init; lab.guild-teardown stops it. Open questions: (1) timeout / wallclock cap (orientation trial is bounded but other trials might not be), (2) backgrounding mechanics — node child_process.spawn with detached:true + unref, write pidfile, stop with SIGTERM, (3) interaction with the test guild's clockworks daemon (do we use 'nsg start' which boots full daemon, or 'nsg crawl-continual' which is just spider's loop), (4) crash recovery if the lab-host crashes mid-trial — what happens to the orphaned test-guild process. Spec: spider/clerk are in the published plugin set @ 0.1.292 so they install fine; the test guild needs spider + clockworks added to its plugin pin list. After this lands, X016 phase 2 trial can run waitForTerminal=true and the implementer rig actually executes. Captures real animator/sessions data (turn counts, costs, durations) for orientation-tax analysis.",
        "status": "live"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-momm4i15-35752bcd0118",
        "goal": "Daemon vs CLI Scriptorium state drift — \"nsg codex remove\" from the CLI runs in a separate process and updates guild.json, but the running daemon in-memory Scriptorium state is not notified. The daemon next guild.json write reverts the orphan removals. Vibers currently has three cosmetic orphan codexes (verify-fixtures-{1267530e,2244ce82,40dd2663}) that will only clear on daemon restart. Cosmetic (orphan bare repos do not run code) but means CLI-side cleanup does not stick. Possible fixes: (1) CLI-side codex-remove signals the daemon via Clockworks event to reload Scriptorium, OR (2) Scriptorium adopts a watch-and-reconcile pattern on guild.json changes, OR (3) document the daemon-restart requirement and fail-loud when CLI-side codex changes are made with a daemon running.",
        "status": "live"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-momm4abc-388d14dfcd53",
        "goal": "Failed-trial orphan cleanup — when guild-setup fails after codex-setup succeeds, the rig fails without running teardowns, leaving codexes registered in the lab-host's Scriptorium and bare repos on disk. Two design directions: (1) setup engines grab a release-on-rig-terminal handle that fires on any rig terminal-state, OR (2) teardowns run unconditionally on rig failure (currently they only run when the upstream chain succeeded). Surfaced during live verifies. Cosmetic for now (orphans don't run code) but failed-trial dev loops accumulate cruft.",
        "status": "live"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-momkqtn5-a4b78b70bcf0",
        "goal": "Implement lab.archive engine — read probe yields from upstream context, write one row to lab-trial-archives with id+trialId+archivedAt+probes[{id, engineId, summary}]. Atomic per-row via SQLite. Replace the current archive-presence safety check on teardown engines from 'context.upstream.archive defined' to 'archive row exists for this trialId'. Conclude this click on implementation; design conclusion lives at sibling c-momaa5o9 and full spec at packages/laboratory/README.md.",
        "status": "concluded"
      },
      {
        "id": "c-momkil4p-ecddfc1c0442",

